    <segment id="1" parent="38" relname="span">I tend to believe that intuitiveness is partly learned.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="3" relname="background"> 
Take the light switch as an example.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="21" relname="span"> 
The on-off switch is a fairly basic design.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="19" relname="span"> 
However, designers have changed the light switch over the years to make it more appealing and to bring more functionality to it.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="4" relname="elaboration"> 
These days a light switch can be a round wheel that has to be pushed in to turn on the light.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="4" relname="elaboration"> 
The same switch can be rotated to dim the lights or make them brighter.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="17" relname="concession"> 
While simplicity is still there, </segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="20" relname="span">
the user experience with this light switch is different, </segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="34" relname="span">
and it might be argued that it has to be learned.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="22" relname="antithesis"> 
One might decide to try to &quot;pull out&quot; the light switch to toggle on,</segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="32" relname="span"> rather than push in, </segment>
    <segment id="31" parent="22" relname="elaboration">
or one might think just turning the wheel will turn it on or off.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="32" relname="background"> 
Actually, I think some of these switches do work differently depending on the design.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="27" relname="span"> 
The bottom line is not everything, including light switches, are necessarily intuitive.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="36" relname="span"> 
Bad design, says Don Norman, can get in our way of using every day things.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="13" relname="background"> 

Norman uses the examples of doors.</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="28" relname="span"> 
In some fancy hotels, it is unclear whether one is to push in a glass door or pull the handle.</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="23" relname="nonvolitional-cause"> 
Some doors do not have knobs or handles,</segment>
    <segment id="23" parent="24" relname="span"> 
so which direction does one push or pull?</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="30" relname="span"> 
Again, part of it is about fancy design getting in the way of usability.</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="29" relname="span"> 
Web sites are probably the worst violators of all </segment>
    <segment id="26" parent="15" relname="nonvolitional-cause">
given design is often a free for all.</segment>
